title: Printable Linear Bearing and Rail System - Draft 2

description.text:
This is the second draft of work towards a linear bearing and rail system containing only one non-printed part, the rolling elements (6mm airsoft BBs). Why airsoft BBs? They're cheap, they're round, they're biodegradable, and they're easy to get.
The system is currently at the "workingish" stage of development. The original draft from a year ago proved to have some major problems when I finally was able to print it, so I threw a lot of stuff from it out and focused on getting something that rolled. As a result, there are 3 non-printable parts in this thing - the balls, M3 screws left over from my makerbot assembly, M3 nuts to go with them. I printed it and it rolls alright, with a bit more play than I'm really happy with. If your tolerances are better/different from mine, you will probably get different results.

The bearing itself is made of 2 Half-Bearing pieces, 1 Retainer piece, 2 M3 screws, 2 nuts, and 32 BBs (16 in each race). BBs can be inserted during assembly, or after assembly by pushing them in between the retainer and the bearing. Chances are some will fall out and need to be pushed back in at some point.
If you're printing this, I recommend starting with 2 Half Rail pieces and 2 Rail Brace pieces. M3 screws should pass through the holes in the rails and thread into the braces, but your mileage may vary. This should be enough to check if the parts are coming off your machine in working order. To expand the rail by one length, print 2 Half Rail pieces and one Rail connector piece. Replace one brace with one end of the connector and move the brace to the new end of the rail. The image I posted is 3 lengths long, containing 6 Half Rail pieces, 2 Connectors, and 2 Braces in total.

These pieces can be assembled to create a square pot-holder loom. Depending on how you assemble it, you can either make small (10cm) or medium sized (20cm) square looms. A pot-holder loom is one of the simplest ways to begin weaving, as it has no moving parts. This one is best suited to bulky yarns, but can be used for lighter yarns if you can double them up. Printed at 0.3mm with hollow fill on an UP Mini. (As a side note, the 20cm loom is a perfect size for blanket squares, if you feel like crafting for charity.)

To assemble a small (10cm) loom, print four straight pieces and four corner pieces. Slot the ends of the straight pieces into the corner slots to create a square. The "hooks" of the straight pieces will be facing outward.  
To assemble a larger (20cm) loom, print eight straight pieces, four corner pieces, and four straight_join pieces. Connect the straight pieces in pairs using the straight_join pieces to make 20cm long lengths, then use the four corner pieces to combine into a square.  
To weave using standard, bulky yarn, wrap the end of the yarn around one of the corner pieces, then wrap the yarn around the hooks on opposite ends until each hook has yarn on it. These are the warp threads. Do not pull the yarn too tightly, or your loom will bend (or possibly even snap).  
Now, take the remaining yarn, wrap it around one of the side hooks, and weave it alternately over and under the warp threads. Wrap it around a hook, and repeat the process in the other direction.

description.text: Absolutely the last one for the Zortrax M200 printer...promise.
Re-design of a mesh from Ecelon/Mystie.  Have fun!

A convenient way to store your Rockwell Jawhorse out of the way. Mounts to the wall with five #10 screws. I would recommend printing with a very high infill, I used 55% and it's had no signs of failure yet. To enable the Jawhorse to be wall mounted requires removing the plastic roller on the bottom of the clamp, instructions are provided below. Will not work with the RK9002 Sheetmaster model.

Removal of the roller is very simple and only requires a phillips screwdriver. Step One:
Remove screws circled in red, loosen both screws circled in green. After this is done the front cover printed with the word "JAWHORSE" should pull straight out. Step Two:
Remove both screws circled in green, loosen one screw circled in blue and remove the other screw circled in blue. This will allow the roller to pivot out. After the roller has been pivoted it out you can slide it off its axle. Step Three:
Pivot the axle back into place and put the screws back in revers order. Your Jawhorse is now ready to be wall mounted.

description.text:
Single walled low res hi quality cup, printed is 17min 12 sec...!
see also facebook.com/europerminutedesign

The trick:
  • use a 0.8 mm nozzle [instead of standard 0.4mm]
  • print with layerheight 0.4
  • with skeinforge 39 [or higher] use fill, with solidity 0
  • to get a nice bottom set the 'extra shells on alternating solid layers' and the 'extra shells on base layers' on 999
  • for raftless printing: turn ON raft and set the base and interface layers on 0
    set the first layer feed and flow rates at 0.25
  • to not close the vase: remove the to 2 layers in the gcode file
  • heat up and go!
    • tip for skeinforge developpers: will it be possible to have a top/bottom/both feature...?

This is a case for the GoPro Hero HD Camera. I printed this in soft PLA material. It was designed to be mounted on a R/C model airplane. Like this it is possible to use it as FPV camera. --> FPV: First Person View; more info on:
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Person_View

• Print (preferably in soft material - I use soft PLA)
  • Clean from burrs and drips
  • Open Hole with a knife (for rubber band - see photo)
  • Screw in place
  • Fix camera inside with a rubber band
    • PS: There are two files - the case and a GoPro model. you might want to use the GoPro model eventually if you have your own plans with the GoPro and if you're fed up in first use calipers to measure yours or to print it out and test fit before you buy it. I think it should be modeled quite accurate.

Had a 3 gang switch plate that only had 1 remaining switch (dimmer) in use.  It was that way when I moved into the house.  Instead of buying a new 3 gang plate with just 1 switch hole and the rest solid to clean it up, I decided to keep the plate and design a blank that would secure the plate and fill the empty switch hole.  I made a few versions and the one I like the most is the thin solid version.  Needs minimal support and only 7 grams of filament to print.  It holds perfect to the box and gives great support to the plate using standard screws.  Feel free to try the others if you like.  Looks a lot better than empty holes in the plate.  I printed mine white since my plate was white.  Not sure if they have almond filament.  Didn't see any other models out there like this and decided to share for anyone else needing a quick solution to a remodel/rewired switch box.  Let me know what you think and if you print any please share how it fit your application.  Enjoy and happy printing.
Note: The green wire tied to the screw made me laugh to see it that way on the box when I took the cover off.  So I kept it in the same location after install to take the pic.  I've since put it where it belongs.

description.text:
The B9C slicer works very well (I verified version 1.4). B9C slicer is great in that it can deal with millions of faces and also with intersecting faces. In the attached files and photos, I was testing the following scenario:
features with very small differences in height. This STL is for testing at 50.8 micron layers. It contains:
  • a set of cylinders, the first being 5.06 mm tall,
  • a set of pentagonal extrusions, the first being 5.06+0.025 mm tall,
  • a set of hexagonal extrusions, the first being 5.06+0.040 mm tall.
    • Within each set, each subsequent extrusion is 50.8 micron taller than the precedent, so its "roof" feature should be located in each subsequent layer after slicing. The slicer works as expected: inside the B9J files, one can see just the expected case described above. If you wish to see this effect with your eyes (rather than in the B9C software or with a caliper), you can print the "_printable" version of the STL. Its base is 5 mm tall.

To test the slicer, you do not need to print:
simply open a B9J file in "Main Menu"/"Edit", and look at the last layers to be printed. The settings for the print are:
50.8 micron z, 50 micron xy.

This 4x4x4 version of 3D Tic Tac Toe is what I grew up with: I like it much better than some of the 3x3x3 versions you see because this almost never ends in a draw.  The strategy is actually pretty involved.  3D printed, 3D Tic Tac Toe?... why not?  The Xs and Os are the same piece designs from what I've had on Shapeways previously: I'm uploading the piece designs here, along with an improved stand design.
The improved stand (see renders) can be printed as 4 separate units which stack one atop the other. It's better than the original one (pictured) because 1) it means you can partially disassemble the stand to access some of the middle spaces if you need to, 2) pieces could fall through the old grid design, and 3) although the double helix supports are kinda neat, it made the whole thing quite springy which is not a great quality in a stand. 
I hope you like it, and invite you to check out some of my newer designs on my Shapeways store (I put them up at shapeways.com/shops/mikelepage first, then may move them here later if there's enough interest).

description.text: I was in the need of a new extruder for my TAZ, so I thought why not use my recent customizations to my other printers? As I was using the L3K extruder and it performs good enough I started this little project to create an adapter to attach an L3K extruder to the TAZ. It has two parts: The first is just the plate to be attached to the TAZ's gantry. Easy to print on ABS as it is flat. The second part is the real L3K adapter that keeps firmly attached the extruder to the plate. Modular design to be able to redesign one part without reprint the whole thing. Remember to add support to the touchplate in the L3K adapter, I choose to print it this way to increase the strength of the part in the X direction (where the stress is on). You will need some M4 bolts, a M3 long bolt ans some nuts, and of course the L3K extruder. See also my other L3K extruder designs for possible improvements.

title: Knob for Encoder/ Drehknopf für Encoder, Ultimaker, Mankati, Witbox

description.text:
Bei vielen Druckern, so auch beim Mankati, werden Encoder als Eingabetool genutzt. Das sind die Drehknöpfe, mit denen man das gewünschte Menü auswählt und es dann durch drücken auf den Knopf bestätigt. Doch diese Encoder haben eine sehr geringen Drehwiderstand, deshalb passiert es sehr oft, das man mit dem Drücken des Knopfes auch unwillkürlich eine Drehbewegung macht und so das falsche Menü auswählt. Das nervt auf die Dauer. Man kann das ändern, indem man einen anderen Encoder einbaut, z. B. diesen hier: http://www.conrad.de/ce/de/product/700697/Encoder-5-VDC-001-A-360-ALPS-STEC11B03-1-St Oder man trennt die Drehbewegung und das Drücken des Knopfes. Das passiert bei dem hier gezeigten Drehknopf. Drehen lässt der sich ganz normal. Und den Eingabedruck führt man aus, indem man auf die Kugel drückt. Und diese kann keine Drehbewegungen übertragen, wenn diese sich im Drehknopf frei bewegen kann. Eine Kugel ist bei den Bauteilen dabei, die kann man drucken mit feiner Auflösung. Besser ist jedoch eine Stahlkugel von etwa 12mm Durchmesser. This button separation of rotational movement and pressing for the printer controller. Many Printers use a cheap Encoder. One makes when entering involuntarily a rotary motion, but I just want to Press. And then I have the wrong menu.
With this button you can solve the problem because of the ball. You can print the ball, better is a iron ball. Have fun!

description.text:
One Light to burn them all :-)
A little sunday afternoon project and my 2ct for a better world; old and "empty" cells can be reused down to 0,5V. This flashlight works with AAA, AA and coin cells. With a little change in the inside you can also put in a 9V battery. Specs:
  • 2x 3V white LEDs
  • AAA or AA cells (2 cells possible)
  • Coin cells (stackable)
  • 9V block (the wall between "AAA" and "electronics" needs to be removed)
  • works with 1 cell down to 0.5V to produce 3V
    • electronic parts:
  • 2 LEDs: white; max 3V
  • 2 Coils: 470 uH
  • Resistor: 32k Ohm
  • Transistor: f.e. BC548
  • capacitor: 680 pF
  • micro switch: f.e. US # MJTP1119 / EU # PHAP3351 (you can also update the design to put in any other kind of switch)
  • spare piece of circuit board (max 6.8 x 1.3cm or 2.5x2.5cm if you want to use the space of the coin cell)
  • optional: coin cell holder (fe. for CR2032 cells)
    • Please feel free to update the design, change the button part or put the electronics in the place of the coin cell to use 2 AAA cells. cheers
    chris

  • release the brake arm back to the spool to hold it in place and avoid unwanted movement.
  • pull the wire through the little hole infront of the spool like a Tesafilm holder.
  • Enjoy!

A wildly experimental prototype modular mounting system for the MPCNC power supply and RAMPS 1.4, volts/amps meter panel (blinky lights and such), laser driver and a Raspberry Pi 2 Model B (AstroPrint/Octoprint).
Everything is modular and I'm including STEP files to make it easy to modify in case you want to use it for something else.
Seriously down the rabbit hole on this one in case you hadn't noticed. The upside is, it works.

The original idea was to design something that can easily be printed in a 6" (155mm) work envelope. The supports are two 8" lengths of left over 1" EMT. With a 0.93" diameter and a 3mm wall the first job was to figure out how to print a larger hexagon in two or more pieces. Two pieces of EMT and two brackets look to be a reasonable place to start. Panel Volt Meter - 4.5V to 30VDC
https://www.adafruit.com/products/575 Panel Current Meter - 0 to 9.99A
https://www.adafruit.com/products/574 Panel Temperature Meter / -30 to +70 °C
https://www.adafruit.com/products/576 2015-10-22 UPDATE
Added a remix provision for the RepRap Discount Smart Controller. The cover is trimmed to print on my 6x6x6 format 3D printer. 2015-10-18 UPDATE
Assembled, powered up and tested .. looks real good. Had a minor edit and reprint on the laser driver bracket. Other than that it came together neatly. Soldering is not required if you use one of these above the shunt on the ammeter (much better than wire nuts). Snap-action 3-Wire Block Connector
https://www.adafruit.com/products/866 2015-10-10 UPDATE
After working through a number of test prints and minor design changes it's doing what I need for this project so time to wrap it up and move on. The only real difference from the original is the way the mounts attach to the EMT. Instead of slipping over, these snap around. It's much easier to work with but a little less rigid so to compensate I added the coupling locks.

description.header: Tool for splitting  bigger model like terrain into printable tiles.
description.text:
Using Bash and OpenSCAD binaries, created on Linux, but it can be for sure use under cygwin or in any linux virtualmachine. Usage: bash ./TileSplitter.sh --sourceModel "SourceModel.stl" --outputName "OutputModelName" What tool does: Tool Output are tiles in STL format of specified tileSizeX and tileSizeY in directory Output.
Tool also can cut bottom of tile to decrease printable size if possible.
Tool expects sourceModel is sitting on Z 0 or it can be adjusted with offset argument, same X and Y offsets. Adresses are now counted from 1x1, because I added dots for identify Xaddress(bottom X side) and squares for Y address(left Y side). Tool arguments and example defaults:

  • source model
    sourceModel="Example.stl";

  • offset on X axis, depends on source model
    modelOffsetX=300

  • offset on Y axis, depends on source model
    modelOffsetY=300

  • offset on Z axis, depends on source model
    modelOffsetZ=0

  • maximum size on axis X, to be able create boolean objects
    modelSizeX=800

  • maximum size on axis Y, to be able create boolean objects
    modelSizeY=800

  • maximum size on axis Z, to be able create boolean objects
    modelSizeZ=100

  • size on X for one tile
    tileSizeX=160

  • size on Y for one tile
    tileSizeY=160

  • size on Z which will be cut from bottom
    tileSizeCutBottom=20

  • destination where tiles will be saved
    outputDir="Output"

  • base name for output stl files
    outputName="ExampleTile"

  • draw identifiers dot for X, square for Y address (1 means on 0 off)
    drawSideNumbers=1
